quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
  41,47,"To Him is referred<i class=""s"">(all) </i>knowledge of the Hour. And <span class=""h"">no products<sup foot_note=""81072"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">come out of their sheaths</span>nor does any female carry or deliverbut with His knowledge. And on the day when He calls out to them, “Where are My associates?” They said{2}, “We declare to You, none of us is a witness.”",footnotes:2:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.
  41,48,"And whatever they used to call upon earlier strayed away from them, and they realized that there was no escape for them."
  41,49,"Man never tires of supplication for good things, but if evil touches him, he becomes despairing, despondent."
  41,50,"And if We do let him taste a mercy from Us after an adversity that has touched him, he will surely say, “This is mine, and I do not think that the Hour is coming. And even if I am returned to my Lord, I will have the very best with Him.” We will inform those who denied of what they did, and We will make them taste a harsh punishment."
  41,51,"And when We bestow Our blessings upon Man, he disregards<i class=""s"">(Us) </i>and distances himself. But when evil touches him, he has lengthy supplication."
  41,52,"Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Have you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>seen? If it is from Allah and then you deny it—who is more misguided than he who is in profound discord?”"
  41,53,"We will show them Our signs in the horizons and in themselves until it becomes evident to them that He{1}is the Truth. Is it not sufficient that your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord is witness over everything?",footnotes:1:The Arabic pronoun can mean ‘He’ for God or ‘it’ for the Qur’an or Islam.
  41,54,"Undoubtedly, they do regard the meeting with their Lord with skepticism. Undoubtedly, He is indeed All-Encompassing of everything."
